336 HORATII FLACCI

SATIRE II.

This Satire appears to have been written on the death of Tigellius,a musician of great re- pnte, who, as we learn from the opening verse of the next Satire, was on terms of familiar intimacy with C. Julius Caesar. The Scholiasta who call him M. Hermogenes Tigellius say that he afterwards became a favour-ite with Cleopatra, and then again with Augustus. Acron says Horace quarrelled with him because he found fault with the rhythm of his verses. It is probable that this Tigellius is miscalled M. Hermogenes, and that this name belongs only to another Tigellius who was also a singer mentioned in S. 3. 1293 4. 723 9. 253 10. 18, 80, 90. These persons had never been separated till Dacier distinguished between them. Heindorf adheres to the old opinion, which 1 think has been satisfactorily disposed of by Kirchner in his treatise ‘³ De Utroque Tigellio '⁹ , (Quaest. Hor. p. 42, sqq.). The Tigellius of this Satire is called Sardus, a Sardinian, ixi the next (v. 3). It appears from the Scholiasts that he was attacked by Licinius, from whom they quote this verse: ‘⁸ Sardi Tigelli putidum caput venit.” He was probably therefore a libertinus. Cicero had a quarrel with this person, whose influence with Caesar was such that it made him rather anxious, though he affecta in some of his letters to hold the man cheap. Compare Epp. ad Fam. vii. 24. Ad Att. xiii. 49. 50, and 51. He too alludes to Licinius’ verse, and calls Tigellius “ hominem pestilentiorem patria sua (the climate of Sardinia was eounted very bad) addictum jam dudum Calvi Licinii Hipponacteo praeconio ’³ (Ad Fam. 1. c.). The character of Tigellius is drawn cleverly in the opening verses of the next Satire.

The statement of the Scholiasta on v. 25 of this Satira, that some supposed (so Porph. and Cotum. Cruq. put it3 Acron says at once “Maecenatem tangit'') that, under the name Malchinus, Horace means to satirize Maecenas, seems to me unworthy of the least ‹n-edit. But it has had warm defenders, and upon this assumption the date of the Satira is fixed, both Kirchner and Franks placing it in A.u.c. 714, in order to allow sufficient time between the composition of the libel, and the introduction of Horace to his patron. 1 will not trouble the reader by going into the argument, except to say that, if the libel was keen enough to offend, it is as improbable Horace would have published as that he would have written it, aster his introduction to Maecenas3 and if (as appears to me) there is nothing to offend in the verse, it was as probably written after as before their acquaint- ance began. But 1 do not believe Maecenas had any thing to do with the verse at all. An early date must be assigned to the Satira, because it certainly preceded the 4th, and that again was composed before the 10th of this Book. Whether the coarseness of the ideas and language, and the want of artistic arrangement and connexion, may not be an argument for an early date, deserves consideration. (See Introduction to S. 4.) It is without exception the coarsest of all Horaee’s Satires, and, with reference to the point it professes to turn upon, the least to the purpose. 1 can traco no connexion between the text which is contained in v. 24 (⁸⁴ fools trying to avoid one class of vices run into their oppositas ”) and the licentious lang-uage and advice contained in the latter half of the Satire, which in brief amounts to this: ⁴ do not let a false ambition lead you into intriguing with married women, but make yourself happy with prostitutas: The examples which appear to be to the purpose are not so in reality. Tigellius, we may be sure, did not give his money to harlots and impostors in order to avoid the character of a miser3 nor did Fufidius drive hard usurious bargains, cheat young men with good ex· pectations, and deny and torment himself, in order to avoid the charge of extravagance.
